241
26:36.120 --> 26:40.350
and here we can see the
result of doing that.

242
26:40.350 --> 26:47.820
For the first term, the standard basis state
of the top qubit is 0, so f of zero gets XORed
onto the bottom qubit,

243
26:47.820 --> 26:53.970
and that works by linearity. And it's similar for the second term, except that the standard basis state

244
26:53.970 --> 26:59.520
for the top qubit is 1, so we XOR f of 1 onto the bottom qubit.

245
26:59.520 --> 27:08.250
And at this point, we can
simplify this expression by observing the formula
that you can see down here, which works when a is either 0 or 1.

246
27:08.250 --> 27:12.270
And we can simply check this for those two values separately.

247
27:12.270 --> 27:19.251
If a is equal to 0, then
XORing with a does nothing, and negative 1 to the power 0 is 1,

248
27:19.251 --> 27:25.680
so the two sides are equal. And if a is equal to 1, we get cat 1 minus cat
0 when we take the XOR,

249
27:25.680 --> 27:31.110
which is negative 1
times cat 0 minus cat 1.

250
27:31.110 --> 27:38.850
And if we use that formula
to simplify our state, where we take a is equal
to f of 0 on the left and a is equal to f of 1 on the right,

251
27:38.850 --> 27:42.690
we get the expression
that you see right here.

252
27:42.690 --> 27:49.290
So when we compare the two
quantum state vectors π1 and π2, we see that what the Uf gate does

253
27:49.290 --> 27:56.460
is effectively to put
one of the two values, f of 0 or f of 1, into the
exponent of negative 1,

254
27:56.460 --> 28:00.750
or in other words, into
the phase of each term.

255
28:00.750 --> 28:10.050
This is the reason for
initializing the bottom qubit to 1 and performing a Hadamard gate on it to create the minus state,
which allows this to happen.

256
28:10.050 --> 28:16.980
It's called the phase kickback phenomenon, and we'll come back to it in a few moments to have another look at it.

257
28:16.980 --> 28:27.120
It's pretty important, and we'll see it happening a
few more times in the lesson, as well as in later lessons.

258
28:27.120 --> 28:34.140
We can now simplify by pulling
the minus state back outside to get the expression
that you see right here.

259
28:34.140 --> 28:39.330
As an aside, it's kind
of interesting to notice that there isn't actually
any entanglement here.

260
28:39.330 --> 28:45.360
Both of these states are product states. So, well, entanglement
is extremely interesting,

261
28:45.360 --> 28:51.120
doesn't happen to be
playing any role at all in this particular algorithm.

262
28:51.120 --> 28:56.940
Let's clean this up a bit so that we have a little bit more room.

263
28:56.940 --> 29:03.210
What we can now do is to
pull a factor of negative 1 raised to the power f of zero outside

264
29:03.210 --> 29:07.800
to get the expression of the
state that you see right here.

265
29:07.800 --> 29:14.790
You'll notice that right here, we have eXclusive OR of f 0 and f 1 in the exponent of negative 1.

266
29:14.790 --> 29:22.200
We might expect that to
be f of 1 minus f of 0 because we pull the factor of negative 1 to the power f of 0 out,

267
29:22.200 --> 29:30.000
but we get the same
value if we take the XOR because these are bits, and the only thing that matters when we have an integer in
the exponent of negative 1

268
29:30.000 --> 29:36.300
is whether that integer is even or odd.

269
29:36.300 --> 29:43.410
Another way to express this
state is like we have here, where we're just considering
the two possible cases for the XOR.

270
29:43.410 --> 29:52.950
and that's a convenient
way to express the state as we consider the action
of the final Hadamard gate together with the measurement.

271
29:52.950 --> 29:59.550
When we perform the last
Hadamard gate on the top qubit, the plus state is
transformed into a 0 state

272
29:59.550 --> 30:10.980
and the minus state is
transformed into a 1 state, which we can write more
succinctly like this.

273
30:10.980 --> 30:19.230
And finally, when the
measurement is performed, the result we obtain is
therefore the XOR of f 0 and f 1,

274
30:19.230 --> 30:26.520
which is the value we're looking for, and that's how Deutsch's algorithm works.

275
30:26.520 --> 30:33.480
It's pretty simple, and if we ask ourselves what
it is that makes it work, allowing us to compute
the parity of two bits

276
30:33.480 --> 30:40.440
with a single query rather than two, a reasonable answer is
that it's interference.

277
30:40.440 --> 30:46.590
We're effectively
computing f of 0 and f of 1 at the same time, because we first performed
the Hadamard gate

278
30:46.590 --> 30:53.370
on the top qubit to put the input into f into
a super position of 0 and 1.

279
30:53.370 --> 30:59.580
And by means of the phase kickback together with the final Hadamard gate, we're essentially creating
constructive interference

280
30:59.580 --> 31:03.540
for the correct answer and destructive interference
for the wrong answer.

281
31:03.540 --> 31:08.160
So we don't see the wrong answer, we only see the correct answer.

282
31:08.160 --> 31:16.050
Let me now say a bit more about the phase kickback phenomenon just to see it from a
slightly different angle.

283
31:16.050 --> 31:23.790
First, let's observe
this very simple formula where b and c are arbitrary binary values.

284
31:23.790 --> 31:31.530
In short, XORing a bit b by the value 1 is the same thing as performing a NOT gate or an x operation on b,

285
31:31.530 --> 31:39.510
and of course, exploring
a bit b by the value 0 doesn't do anything to it, which is the same thing as performing the
identity operation on it.

286
31:39.510 --> 31:44.910
And we can express the identity operation as x to the power 0.

287
31:44.910 --> 31:51.900
So if we perform a Uf gate on two qubits in the standard basis
state cat b tensor cat a,

288
31:51.900 --> 31:57.600
we obtain this outcome, just by the definition of the Uf gate.

